    "text": "[@aljoscha](@zurF8X68ArfRM71dF3mKh36W0xDM8QmOnAS5bYOq8hA=.ed25519)\r\n\r\nRight, I think there are two problems:\r\n\r\n- variations we know about when publishing\r\n- variations we learn about later\r\n\r\nPublishing `{ \"flipped\": true }` is great when you know you're publishing a distinct message flavor that other clients might have trouble understanding. Publishing `{ \"userAgent\": \"oasis@2.1.3\" is great when you realize, months later, that you were accidentally publishing buggy messages and you want to be able to retroactively declare that messages posted with a client use some variation like `{ \"upsideDown\": true }`.\r\n\r\nPersonally, I'd be happy to support both of these.\r\n\r\nI'd love a shared [multiformats-style table](https://github.com/multiformats/multiaddr/blob/master/protocols.csv) where we share well-known semantics. For example:\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n  \"patchbay\": {\r\n    \"version\": \"*\",\r\n    \"flavors\": {\r\n      \"flipped\": false\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  \"oasis\": {\r\n    \"version\": \"*\",\r\n    \"flavors\": {\r\n      \"flipped\": true\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```",
